of our colleagues managed to

00:22:10.180 --> 00:22:13.910
get on board with their
government delegation, like in

00:22:13.910 --> 00:22:17.370
Kenya, probably also Uganda.

00:22:17.370 --> 00:22:22.410
We have been hearing different
updates, if you

00:22:22.410 --> 00:22:25.510
will, from the grounds--

00:22:25.510 --> 00:22:27.620
and possibly also
Cote d'Ivoire.

00:22:27.620 --> 00:22:32.970
Anyway, as Africa internet
policy progenitor, I'm not

00:22:32.970 --> 00:22:35.160
focusing particularly
on [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:35.160 --> 00:22:36.250
countries.

00:22:36.250 --> 00:22:43.250
And I am in the position of
being kind of an observatory

00:22:43.250 --> 00:22:49.250
of how different governments,
different countries in the

00:22:49.250 --> 00:22:55.890
continent progressing on the
issue of being more inclusive,

00:22:55.890 --> 00:23:00.300
being multi-stakeholder in their
policy making processes.

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:05.530
And there has been some low
progress in that regard.

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:11.585
Now coming back to the WCIT's
agenda itself, I believe as a

00:23:11.585 --> 00:23:16.880
couple of my colleagues said,
it's really about power

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:20.340
struggle and about control.

00:23:20.340 --> 00:23:21.720
Control can be political.

00:23:21.720 --> 00:23:27.840
It can be under the guise of
a [INAUDIBLE] security.

00:23:27.840 --> 00:23:32.320
It can be about controlling
people and their freedom of

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:35.980
expression and constraining
those rights.

00:23:35.980 --> 00:23:42.340
It can also be about commerce
and financial reasons.

00:23:42.340 --> 00:23:46.730
What is happening here is that
at the core of the issues is

00:23:46.730 --> 00:23:57.850
the fact that government, since
the last 1988 treaty, we

00:23:57.850 --> 00:24:00.440
have seen a lot of things
change in the--

