I mean, I think Carolina and
Pilar raise a really important

00:30:21.390 --> 00:30:23.230
point about the need for

00:30:23.230 --> 00:30:26.450
in-language access to documents.

00:30:26.450 --> 00:30:30.170
But I want to comment a little
bit about the notion of, we

00:30:30.170 --> 00:30:31.930
don't really know what's
going on here.

00:30:31.930 --> 00:30:33.530
I think--

00:30:33.530 --> 00:30:36.910
we saw on day one, and it was
only on the first day of the

00:30:36.910 --> 00:30:39.660
conference that we find out
whether civil society that was

00:30:39.660 --> 00:30:42.990
not on a government delegation
was going to get in at all.

00:30:42.990 --> 00:30:44.690
They were-- that vote
did go well.

00:30:44.690 --> 00:30:48.970
They did allow society to be
at the conference venue, to

00:30:48.970 --> 00:30:53.510
attend the plenary sessions and
the Committee 5 sessions.

00:30:53.510 --> 00:30:55.830
That's sort of where the bulk
of the treaty writing is

00:30:55.830 --> 00:30:57.650
getting done.

00:30:57.650 --> 00:31:01.050
But what we've already seen in
just four days of conference,

00:31:01.050 --> 00:31:02.760
and only actually less than
that in terms of real

00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:09.920
substantive debate, is that
as massive debates divide.

00:31:09.920 --> 00:31:10.850
It's very contentious.

00:31:10.850 --> 00:31:14.830
And the chair of the WCIT is
pushing a lot of these issues

00:31:14.830 --> 00:31:17.030
into what are called
working groups.

00:31:17.030 --> 00:31:19.550
This is not working group like
you and I think, it's a couple

00:31:19.550 --> 00:31:20.650
people trying to
hammer it out.

00:31:20.650 --> 00:31:24.210
It's still all 193
member states.

00:31:24.210 --> 00:31:27.850
But civil society is not allowed
to participate in the

00:31:27.850 --> 00:31:29.466
working groups.

00:31:29.466 --> 00:31:31.850
Unlike the plenary sessions
and the full committee

00:31:31.850 --> 00:31:34.920
sessions, they're not
live streamed.

00:31:34.920 --> 00:31:38.690
And so it's really hard to
get information out.

00:31:38.690 --> 00:31:39.870
And we can get--

00:31:39.870 --> 00:31:41.530
those of us who have colleagues
who are on

00:31:41.530 --> 00:31:43.760
government delegations
have some means.

00:31:43.760 --> 00:31:46.320
But then we can't share
that information.

00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:53.250
So again I think you saw the
move for the ITU and its

00:31:53.250 --> 00:31:56.630
member states on the first day,
that to make a decision

00:31:56.630 --> 00:31:59.580
behind closed doors, to give
a modicum of transparency.

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:03.330
And this is really concerning
given the really dangerous

00:32:03.330 --> 00:32:06.140
proposals that we're seeing.

00:32:06.140 --> 00:32:07.690
I think everyone sort
of touched on human

00:32:07.690 --> 00:32:09.530
rights in some way.

00:32:09.530 --> 00:32:14.770
But right now there's a huge
debate about whether to

00:32:14.770 --> 00:32:18.120
include human rights at all in
the treaty, particularly.

00:32:18.120 --> 00:32:22.880
And that's really concerning
when that's juxtaposed with

00:32:22.880 --> 00:32:26.280
proposals like on spam, which
would say that governments can

00:32:26.280 --> 00:32:30.950
block any content that has
no meaningful message.

00:32:30.950 --> 00:32:34.210
That's a really dangerously
subjective term in the hands

00:32:34.210 --> 00:32:36.900
of a government.

00:32:36.900 --> 00:32:39.650
And then when you add that with
the obligation to take

00:32:39.650 --> 00:32:43.130
affirmative steps, to
take measures--

00:32:43.130 --> 00:32:45.100
appropriate measures is
the language used--

00:32:45.100 --> 00:32:46.950
to curtail spam.

00:32:46.950 --> 00:32:52.150
If you look at the right to
know that would allow

00:32:52.150 --> 00:32:55.140
governments to know how their
traffic is routed.

00:32:55.140 --> 00:32:56.995
First of all, that would require
a fundamental overhaul

00:32:56.995 --> 00:32:59.650
of the internet's architecture,
trying to shift

00:32:59.650 --> 00:33:02.800
it more to how traditional
telecommunications work.

00:33:02.800 --> 00:33:05.890
But it would also open the door
to widespread, pervasive

00:33:05.890 --> 00:33:07.440
surveillance.

00:33:07.440 --> 00:33:10.050
And then you have other
proposals, particularly from

00:33:10.050 --> 00:33:12.480
Russia, and I'll stop after
this, just to give you--

00:33:12.480 --> 00:33:14.310
I just want to contextualize
this in terms of what the

00:33:14.310 --> 00:33:14.880
debates are.

00:33:14.880 --> 00:33:17.930
Because human rights is not
the discourse here.

00:33:17.930 --> 00:33:21.680
The Russian proposal would allow
censoring content that

00:33:21.680 --> 00:33:25.410
threatens national unity
and security and is

00:33:25.410 --> 00:33:27.240
of a sensitive nature--

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:30.630
these very ambiguous,
vague terms.

00:33:30.630 --> 00:33:34.970
And so we're seeing a really
contentious debate that's

00:33:34.970 --> 00:33:36.480
happening, actually,
still largely

00:33:36.480 --> 00:33:39.850
outside the public eye.

